<h3 class="p150-item-detail__title" id="4939-lightbox-title">The Boilermaker</h3>
<div class="p150-item-detail__description">
<p>This painting by Derek Fordjour hangs in the Black Cultural Center and pays tribute to Purdue’s black students, faculty, and staff — in particular in relation to the campus protest of 1968. The painting depicts a boilermaker and his hammer, but in lieu of tools, he carries a brick in his tool belt, representing the protest. The mortar on the brick represents Purdue and its decision to build up the University and make it more inclusive. The boilermaker’s hand is reaching out to symbolize the efforts of the University’s black alumni, faculty, and staff who are committed to encouraging students to attend Purdue.</p>
<p><a rel="noopener noreferrer" href="http://collections.lib.purdue.edu/campus/buildings/139" target="_blank"><i class="fas fa-map-marker" aria-hidden=""></i>See the Boilermaker painting at the Black Cultural Center.</a></p>
</div>
