<h3 class="p150-item-detail__title" id="4941-lightbox-title">Foundry Class Book End</h3>
<div class="p150-item-detail__description">
<p> As a land-grant institution, Purdue was charged with creating a practical education in science, technology, and agriculture — as shown on the University seal on this bookend, circa 1910. The foundry-related skill of pouring liquid metal into molds was considered to be one of the fundamental, pragmatic skills required of graduates well equipped to enter the late 19th-century and early 20th-century workforce. Early students created bookends, paperweights, and other cast-iron objects. A project of this quality and complexity would have been the work of an upperclassman.</p>
<p><a rel="noopener noreferrer" href="http://collections.lib.purdue.edu/campus/buildings/19" target="_blank"><i class="fas fa-map-marker" aria-hidden></i>A foundry class book end is on display in the Rudolph Room at Dauch Alumni Center.</a> </p>
