<h3 class="p150-item-detail__title" id="5051-lightbox-title">Four-Leaf Clover</h3>
<div class="p150-item-detail__description">
<p> Virginia Claypool Meredith spotted this four-leaf clover on June 13, 1922, just before the groundbreaking ceremonies of the Purdue Memorial Union; she served as chairwoman of the event. She was the first woman appointed to the board of trustees. A nationally known woman farmer, Meredith was dubbed Queen of American Agriculture and firmly believed that farming is a vocation suited for women, stating, “A cow makes as many — or more — pounds of butter when owned by a woman, as when owned by a man.”</p>
