<h3 class="p150-item-detail__title" id="2501-lightbox-title">Nail from Ladies Hall</h3>
<div class="p150-item-detail__description">
<p>Ladies Hall was built around 1871 and was one of three original buildings on campus. Its design — modeled after a building on the Amherst College campus in Massachusetts — was ornate and quite different from any building on Purdue’s campus then or today. Originally known as Boarding Hall, it housed faculty and their families. When women were admitted to Purdue in 1875, the building became the women’s dormitory, and its name was changed to Ladies Hall. It was razed in 1927; today, Stone Hall stands on its location.</p>
<p><a rel="noopener noreferrer" href="https://goo.gl/maps/YvQtN1w4LF62" target="_blank"><i class="fas fa-map-marker" aria-hidden=""></i>Ladies Hall was located near the present-day site of Stone Hall.</a></p>
</div>
