<h3 class="p150-item-detail__title" id="2220-lightbox-title">Printing Block</h3>
<div class="p150-item-detail__description">
<p>For decades, John T. McCutcheon’s (S’1889, HDR LA’26) 1907 <em>Injun Summer</em> cartoon appeared every autumn on the front page of the <em>Chicago Tribune</em> accompanied by a folksy poem. This wood block was used to print the popular drawing, which was syndicated around the country. Its era ended on October 25, 1992, when it appeared for the last time. Douglas Kneeland, the <em>Tribune</em>’s public editor at the time, said, “‘Injun Summer’ is out of joint with its times. It is literally a museum piece, a relic of another age. The farther we get from 1907, the less meaning it has for the current generation.”</p>
