<h3 class="p150-item-detail__title" id="5055-lightbox-title">Quonset Hut</h3>
<div class="p150-item-detail__description">
<p>Intended to be temporary structures for classes after the post-World War II boom in attendance, Quonset huts became a familiar sight for generations of Purdue students. The <em>Exponent</em> poked fun at the tiny structures as far back as 1946:</p>
<p><em>“In each petite hut the classrooms two, </em></p>
<p><em>Resemble the monkey house at the Columbian Park Zoo… </em></p>
<p><em>Classes in the Quonset huts are open to all, </em></p>
<p><em>Provided you are not over five feet tall.” </em></p>
<p>Although the last true Quonset hut — a sort of small-scale airplane hangar with arching roof — on central campus was demolished in 1969, the term was adopted to describe all similar stopgap buildings dating from that time. The last cluster of temporary barracks from the era remained on campus until 2004 when four structures — then housing art, design, and theater classes — were razed to make way for the Armstrong Hall of Engineering at Stadium and Northwestern Avenues.</p>
<p><a rel="noopener noreferrer" href="http://collections.lib.purdue.edu/campus/buildings/180" target="_blank"><i class="fas fa-map-marker" aria-hidden=""></i>The last of the WWII temporary buildings were demolished in 2004.</a></p>
</div>
