<h3 class="p150-item-detail__title" id="4946-lightbox-title">The Wall at Harry&#8217;s</h3>
<div class="p150-item-detail__description">
<p>Harry Marack (-A’23) opened Harry’s Chocolate Shop as a soda fountain in 1919 on the corner of State and Pierce Streets, where it stands today. Harry’s started serving beer in the 1930s and remained in the Marack family until it was sold to current owners Herschel and Mary Cook in 1977. The bar’s slogan, Go Ugly Early, is reported to be a play on the antonyms for “come pretty late.” Although it’s rumored that Harry’s was a speakeasy during prohibition, that claim has never been substantiated. No doubt the iconic campus bar has seen questionable activities over the past century. Its walls, covered with patrons’ colorful scrawls, serve as part registry and part diary. If only those walls could talk.</p>
<p><a rel="noopener noreferrer" href="https://www.google.com/maps/place/Harry’s+Chocolate+Shop/@40.4238133,-86.9112037,925m/data=!3m2!1e3!4b1!4m5!3m4!1s0x8812e2aef7021e37:0x3b4a1e663589228f!8m2!3d40.4238092!4d-86.9090097" target="_blank"><i class="fas fa-map-marker" aria-hidden=""></i>Go Ugly Early at Harry’s Chocolate Shop</a></p>
</div>
